        <div class="commentContent">Hi there:  Thank you so much for publishing this information.  I have been recycling for over 25 years now, and have made a point of educating myself regarding what materials are accepted where and by whom.  I have written letters to request that plastics be marked (plastics are not considered recyclable unless identified by type/number according to most recycling facilities - and understandable, given the fact that these materials are different and need to be handled differently). MANY water, juice, milk, condiment, toothpaste, cosmetic, etc, LIDS are still NOT marked with plastic type or number.  It is important that we request of these manufacturers that they mark the lids for recycling and that we then are diligent to look for that information, and utilize it to recycle the items according to type.  I have to admit that I have been very frequently frustrated to hear friends and associates say that they were not aware that plastics are different and that they &quot;...just throw all plastic into the curbside recycling&quot;.  In fact, just today I met another well-educated person who did not know that plastics are numbered.   SO, THANK YOU VERY MUCH FOR PUBLISHING THIS ARTICLE!! :)  I don&#039;t mean to be so righteous, but, &quot;hear, hear!!&quot;; this info is waaayy overdue!! Thanks.  FYI - Many local humane societies will take your old pill vials and lids to reuse for patients that are being medicated in the facilities.  I am a veterinarian in  Mpls, MN, and the Humane Society of MN is a very large, very active organization with five locations processing thousands of animals each year....we can use those pill vials with the lids! And, thank you for letting me &quot;soap box&quot; for a minute! Dr. Vici</div>
    </div>
