                 Brian            </h4>
            <div class="commentDate">
                Feb 21, 2011            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="commentContent">In response to Nelda G.&#039;s comment about glass - there is virtually no entity that recycles glass in the U.S.  When you put your glass in the recycling bin, it is instead ground and used as a road base.  The market for recycled glass died out when PET came onto the market heavily several decades ago.  PET is lighter to ship, cheper to buy, and won&#039;t break, so many companies started bottling their stuff in plastic instead of glass.  However, plastic does leach toxins into your food whenever it is heated (such as that plastic water bottle in the car on a sunny day), which is why I buy food in glass containers whenever possible.  Glass is made from sand (a nearly unlimited natural resource) and is environmentally benign, it won&#039;t contaminate the environment upon disposal and won&#039;t contaminate your food that is stored in it - that&#039;s why they use it in chemistry labs.  It is also re-used as another product (road base) which is less environmentally harmful than recycling because less energy is required for reuse.  Plastic is made from oil, a limited fossil fuel and comes from a soup of chemicals.  Since your community doesn&#039;t recycle glass, why not reuse the bottles?  My wife uses old spaghetti sauce, olive, and pickle jars to can her preserves.  The lids can be reused and will maintain a new vacuum when canning.  Even if your bottles end up in the landfill, at least they won&#039;t be doing the environment any harm.  How many of those plastic bottles blow out of curbside bins or are lost on the way to the recycling center, ending up in our oceans, lakes, and rivers carrying toxins and poisoning wildlife? </div>
    </div>
    <div class="commentWrapper" style="background: url('http://www.recyclebank.com/skin/frontend/enterprise/blank//images/product-line.png') repeat-x scroll center bottom transparent;">
