        <div class="commentDetails">
            <h4 class="username">
                RecycleBank Member Mike Schenker            </h4>
            <div class="commentDate">
                May 12, 2011            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="commentContent">The article said that Aveda does not accept prescription bottle caps.  If you go to their website and look at their cap recycling guide, it clearly says they are accepted.  Earlier in the program they were not.

Also, after reading the comment about Corpus Christi above, I will say what I believe to be true.  I don&#039;t know what Corpus Christi does, but in general, just because a recycling center in a particular city &quot;accepts&quot; #1 - #7 plastic, I would not be so certain that they recycle them all. There has to be a market for them to be recycled. Hopefully they found one for all those different plastics. I think that some cities have decided to accept all plastics to increase total number of households participating. That way the tonnage of the plastics for which there is a reasonably nearby recycling market increases, and the only downside I can think of is that the ones for which there is no market make a stop at the recycling center before being trucked to the landfill where they would have gone to anyway. </div>
    </div>
